atholic priest, who\nvast shot down in the altar of his\nchurch lu Denver.\nHarry Shlppy Seriously Wounded.\nHarry Shlppy Is the most severely\n\"hurt of those injured In tbo affruy.\nl\"c was shot through the breast twice\nand Is probably fatally wounded. Ills\nlather was stabbed in the arm, whllo\nFoley received u bullet lu the wrist.\nMrs. Shlppy was kicked by the des\nperado, but her hurts are slight.\nbillowing the attack squads of po\nlice woic sent into t he Italian aud\nGhetto districts of the city. Places\nknown sis headquarters of secret so\ncieties suspected of anavchlstlo ten\ndencies were raided and a score or\nmore of arrests made. A coroner's In\nquest over the bo'-vy of the anarchist\nwas alt-o started and State's Attorney\nHealy announced that the-giand juiy\nwill be given an opportunity to Inves\ntigate anarchistic organizations in an\nattempt to fasten lesponslblllty foi\ntho attack upon Its instigators. It Is\nalso repotted that Mayor Uusso In\ntends to issue an order forbidding all\nstreet meetings.\nThat the attempt to kill Chief Ship\npy resulted in failure was due largely\nto the policeman's quickness in an\nticipating the purpose of his visitor's\npresence. Tim man bad twice called\nat. the house and asked for the chief.\nA servant informed him that tho chief\ncould not be seen before 0 o'clock.\nWhen he rang the doorbell at the lat\nter bom. the chit l himself answered\nthe call.\nChief Tells Details of Battle.\n\"As I opened the door,\" said Mr\nShlppy later, describing the attack,\n\"the mail raised his lint and I allowed\nhi in to step into the hallway. He\nhanded me an envelope I glanced at\nit and then the thought stiuek me\nthat the man was up to some wrong,\nlie looked lik an anarchist. 1 grabbed\nhis arms ;md called, to my wife, who\nwas in anothei room. When she ran\ninto tin1 hallway, I said: 'Mother,\nsee If this man has a revolver.' She\nfell one of his back pockets, and said\nthat he had. 1 tried to bold him with\none baud and dtaw my revolver with\nthe other, but he jerked away and fell\nAgainst the door. I caught him again,\nand while we were struggling, my\nson, who was upstaiis. started to my\naid. lie was only a lew steps from\ntho bottom of the stairs when the\nman freed one hand, drew his revolver\n'and II red two shots at Hairy. Then\nFoley, vho had been summoned by\nmy daughter, stepped into the hallway,\nand the man shot him The anarchist\nkicked my wife to one side, nnd by\nIbis lime I bad centred my own re\nvolver, and both Foley and I opened\nfire. At my liist -hot, which struck\nhim In tho head, he tell Rut I fired\nthree more, one in bis head and two\nin his body. Two ot Foley's shots also\nstruck the assassin.\"\nWould-Be Assassin Identified.\nThe would-be assassin of Chief Ship-\npy was idcutitiea ns i.azaius Aver-; t\"1\"\"\"1111 l ii.--u m mu tuiM\nb'ueh. a Russian student of anarch-' railroad commission statistics In an er\nistic tendencies, who for three weeks fort to demonstiate the net revenues\nbad lived with two sisters at the home of the roads will bo endangered by\nor Mrs. Harry Pine, 218 Washburn nve-' enforcement of a maximum distance\nnue. He had only been In inerlca tariff. The undui taking was in re\nthree months, having eonio direct here bponso to an ordei of the commission\nfrom Austria, whither he fled from to U'1-' loads to show cause by March\nKishinev two years ago to escape the 10 why such a tariff bhould not bo\npersecution o the Jews In that city, established. Tho committee will try.\nIt was learned thai Chief Shippy's It was said by the railroad traffic men,\nIntel rereuce several weeks ago with to bring about a greater spirit of co\na parade or unemployed men, headed ietatlou between the railroads and\nlS.\"Dr.\" Ben Rellniann. through the the. commission.\nsHoi'tH or Chicago counicn oy me\nrccfbnt nnnnimccmont tlint Emma Gold\nmnn would not be allowed to speak In\npublic In tills citv 1o Avorbnrh to\nntlompt to \"rotnovo\" the nollco bend In\nRussian terrorist fashion\nTho police clulm to haw Informn\ntlon that the 'vould-bp nrtssln ''old\nmeetings wltlt a number of hi? fr'nrt?\nIn tho former's ronjn ovnrv Rnndnv.\ntempting to enter tbo place or to ar\nrest any one In the vicinity whoso ap\npearance gives warrant fop such ac\ntion. INQUIRY INTO TRAIN ORDER\nPublic Hearing on Union Pacific Train\nCancellation March 4.\nLincoln, Feb. 2S. If lrelght business\nIn Nebraska has fallen off to such an\nextent that the Union Pacific road Is\nwan anted In cancelling half its trains\non branch lines, the railroad commis\nsion wants to know about it. To this\nend a public bearing has been ordered\nlor March 4, when the facts and fig\nures to substantiate action already\ntaken by the road must be forthcoming.\nWithin the week, the Union Pacific\nroad took off one freight train a day\non the Manhattan branch through Be\natrice and ordered tri-weokly service\non Hues from Kearney, Grand Island\nand Columbus. The commercial club\nof Norfolk did not sleep on the matter,\nbut mnde a complaint to the railroad\ncommission before the order had time\nto get cold. The railroad quickly no\ntified the commission that the train\nwould be put back and service on this\nlino has already been restored.\nThis brought tho attention of the\ncommission to the order and on repre\nsentations from tho railroads that en\ngines on local freights capable of haul\ning 1,200 tons at a load were making\ndally trips with from eighty to ISO\ntons, the hearing March 1 was ordered.\nNOT SURE OF HIS NAME\nReceive Letters Warning Them on Pen\nalty of Death to Stop War on Saloons. I\nHastings, Neb., March 3. Numerous\nunsigned letters have been received by\nthe various ministers threatening their\nlives if they did not quit the fight\nagainst the suloons. The city ot Hast-'\nlugs Is stirred to a white heat over the\nsaloon question and In u men's mass I\nmeeting, at -which 1,200 voters were\npresent, resolutions were unanimously\nadopted which will make the fight at\nthe next spring election one of license\nor no license. Seven of the leading\nchurches have inaugurated a scries of\nrevival meetings, conducted by tho\nhome ministers, and the Presbyterian\nchurch Is packed every night.\nThat the fight has stirred up the sa\nloon element is manifest by the fact\nthat it has organized and is piepariug\nto defend Its ground.\nEDMISTEN FAILS TO APPEAR\nAlleged Land Fraud Man Said to Be\nSick in Florida.\nOmaha, March 3. J. II. Udinlstcn.\nformer state oil Inspector, who failed\nto appear for trial in the fedeial\ncouit, is nt Interlachen, Fla., suffering\nfiotii a nervous breakdown.\nJudge V. H. M linger announced that\nhe bad received the above information\nin a telegram from D. R. Jones, Ed\nmist en's physician, who said that Ed\nmisteii was in u serious condition and\nwas unable to appear in couit.\nJudge M linger dismissed the Jury\nand the Kdmlstcu case, alleged fraud\nIn land deals, will go over to the April\nterm of court.\nTHREATEN HASTINGS MINISTERS\nKansas City Man Arrested in Lincoln,\nMentally Unbalanced.\nLincoln, March 3 The police ar\nlesled a well dressed young man, sup\nposed to be Albert McMillan of Kan\nsas City. He was at the Burlington\nMntiou and his actions indicated men\ntal unbalance. He said he thought his\nname was .McMillan aud that he had\nbeen in Lincoln two weeks, but a rail\nload ticket put chased at Quincy, 111.,\nFeb, 20, disproved this. Letters on\nhis person indicated that his wile\nlives at Kansas City, anil she has been\nnotified. He had ltt in cash ami a\ndraft for $1,200. He told the police\nsome one was following and trying to\ni do him harm\nRailroads Oppose Distance Tariff\nChicago, Feb. 2!) Representatives\nof several tallroads having lines in\nNebraska met here and appointed a\nI .wllltUllll t IIKI.lllllt ill 4 1 Jt XTil ItMllll ln\n9-HOUR LAW UPHELD\nRAILROADS READY TO COMPLY\nWITh PROVISIONS OF ACT.\nHeads of Railway Systems Believe\nThis Is Only Way They Can Meet\nthe Situation Means Inconvenience\nto Traveling Public.\nWashington, March 2. American\nrailways have mado arrangements to\ncomply with the provisions of the\nnino-hour law. The operation of the\nlaw will mean the employment by rail\nroad companies of several thousand\nadditional operators and the closing\nof a largo number of small stations on\ntho principal systems. Discontinuing\ntelegraph service at many points, It la\nthought, will Induce at least temporary\ninconvenience to traveling nnd ship\nping public. In order to reduce operat\ning expenses, which now seems nec\nessary, tho operating officials of the\nrailways believe that this Is the only\nway that they possibly can meet tho\nsituation with which they are con\nfronted. During the hearing of applications\nfor an extension of the nine-hour law\nby tho interstate commerce commis\nsion some astonishing statements\nwere mado by the operating officials\nof important railways. A good many\nlines, owing to a reduction In their\nrevenues and to their inability to com\nmand tho cash necessary to meet their\npayrolls, have been forced, during the\npast four months, nlmost to the point\nof asking for receivers. In the opln-.\nion of railway officials expressed at\nthe hearing under oath and in private i\nconversation this condition does not\nBcem to have been due to tho enforce-,\nment of regulative laws or to the In\ncapacity of railway maungeineut.\nMost of the railway officials atttlbutu,\nthe difficulty to the unfortunate bank- j\nIng situation which developed last\nSeptember. The railways did not feel\ntins stringency In money until about\ntho 1st of November. In fact, the'\nmouth of October was one of the host\nIn tho history of the business of Amer\nican railroading.\n\"Then without the slightest warning,\"\nII. U. Mudgo, vice president and gen\neral manager of the Rock Island sys\ntem, expressed it, \"we were plunged\nfrom prosperity to adversity. A year\nago our system could not handle tho\ntraffic offered us. Today, we have 11,\n000 idle cars. Five months ago we\nsuffered from a congestion of freight,\nnow we suffer from a congestion of\nempty cars.\"\nWhat is true of the Rock Island Is\ntrue also of scores of other railroads.\nDepression Not Believed Lasting.\nNot a single official of a single rail\nway line who appeared before! the.\ncommission, however, expressed the\nbelief that the present industrial de\npression would bo lasting. It was\nmerely the Inability to command ready\ncash and tho hoarding of money by\npanic striken Individuals which pro\nduced so suddenly the remarkable de\npression, from which all have suf\nlered. They practically uniformly ex\npress confidence that the return of\nprosperity will bo almost as sudden\nas was the coining of adversity, and In\ntheir arguments as to tho enforce\nment of tho nine-hour law they pointed\nout to the commission that such a re\nturn of prosperity might seriously em\nbartass them In complying with tho\nlaw, because It would render difficult\nto command the services of competent\nopeiators in sufficient numbers to\nmeet the needs of prosperous condi\ntions. With four or five exceptions, no im\nportant railroads in the country have\nindicated nn Intention to reduce the\nwages or their employes. As Chair\nman Kuapp of the Interstate com\nmerce commission expressed it: \"So\nfar as I am Informed there Is no con\ncerted action on the pnrt of Amer\nican railway companies to reduce\nwages. Instances or an intention to\nchange tho scale or wages have been\ngiven, but they can be said to be In\nno sense general.\"\nAGAINST SENATOR FULTON'SBILL\nInterstate Commerce Commission Says\nIt Is Unfair to Railroads.\nWashington, March 2.- -Responding\nto a letter ot Inquiiy to the Interstate\ncommerce committee of the senate the\ninterstate commerce commission has\nwritten a letter taking a position In\nopposition to Senator Fulton's bill pro\nhibiting railroad companies from ad\nvancing rates in the face of a protest\nmade by a shipper until the commis\nsion shall have passed' upon tho rea\nsonableness or the Incrense. \"To give\nto tho protest or a single shipper tho\neffect or preventing the advance or\nany rato m'l the reasonableness or\nthat rdvance was affirmatively deter\nmined by the commission,\" says tho let\nter, \"would estnbllsb a hard and fast\nrule of doubtful fairness to the rail\nroads and questionable advantage to\ntbo public. Under existing conditions\nwe are of the opinion that it would be\nunwise to adopt tho arbitrary limita\ntion which this bill proposes whntovor\nmay be found desirable or necessary\nin this regard In tho future.\"\nAndrew Hamilton Dies Suddenly.\nAlbany. N. Y., March 2. Andrew\nHamilton. fimerly counsel for tho\nTho Kind You Have Always\nin use for over 30 years,\nand\njyfyvf'Ls sonal supervision since its infancy.\n'\"CcCCct16 Allow tin Mt tft1onriin vn liV. tttiu.\nAll Counterfeits, imitations and Just-as-good \"aro bnt\nlixperiuiunts that trifle with and endanger the health of\nInfants and Children Experience against Experiment.\nWhat is CASTORIA\nCastoria is a harmless substitute for Castor Oil, Paro\ngrlc, lrops and Soothing SyrHps- It is Pleasant. It\ncontains neither Opium, Morphine nor other Narcotic\nsubstance. Its ago is its guarantee. It destroys Worms\nand allays Feverlslincss. It cures Diarrhoea and Wind\nColic. It relieves Teething Troubles, cures Constipation\nand Flatulency. It assimilates the Food, regulates tho\nStomach and Bowels, giving healthy and natural sleep.\nThe Children's Panacea The Mother's Friend.\nGENUINE CASTORIA ALWAYS\nBears tho\nThe KM You toe Always Bought\nIn Use For Over 30 Years.\nTMC CtNTAUn COMPANY, 7T MimnAV OTftCET, NEW YORK CITY.\nxs'evv Yorit vam ana ouier insurance\ncompanies, and In charge for many\nyears of Insurance litigation and legis\nlative matters in all parts of tho coun\ntry, was found dead in bed nt his\nhome In this city. His death was en\ntirely unexpected, although he has\nbeen falling to some extent ever since\nthe death of Mrs. Hamilton last July.\nAn autopsy disclosed an acute dilation\nof the heart, which must have caused\npractically Instantaneous death at\nsome time during the night.\nLAUDS JUDGE WILFLEY\nPresident .Roosevelt Commends In\nstead of CetiGures Him.\nWashington, March I). President\nRoosevelt's defense of Lobbeus R. Wil\nlley, based on an unnlvtloal review by\nSecietary Hoot of the ehuige. against\nhim, was made public. The charges\nwere preferred by Ioriin Andrews and\nhave been repeated by him before tbo\nhouse committee on the judiciary as\nthe basis ot Impeachment proceed\nings. They relate to Judge Wlllloy'.s\nadministration of the United States\ncourt for China at Shanghai.\nPresident Roosevelt's decision is\ncontained in a letter to Secretary\nHoot. He flrst comments that It ap\npeals that Congiessman Waldo of New\nYork stands sponsor for the charges.\n\"I cordially concur in your finding,\"\nhe continues, 'which is to the effect\nthat Judge Wilfley is not oul Inno\ncent, but is attacked solely because of\nthe fearlessness anil Integrity with\nwhich he has stamped out vice aud\ncrime iu Shanghai. It is clear that\nJudge Wilfley has been attacked not\nbecause he has done evil, but because\nbe has done good. The assault on him\nIs simply an impeachment of decency\nand zeal for the public good and if\nsuccessful would tend to cow and dls\ncoinage every honest public servant\nwho dares to withstand the forces\nbanded together tor evil and would do\ngrave damage to tho honor aud Inter\nest of our country in the Orient. If\nthe attack were to succeed the bene\nficiaries would be every keeper of a\nhouse of prostitution, every swindling\nlawyer, every man who lives by black\nmall and corruption in the cities of the\nfar east. Those are the people whoso\nhopes have been revived by the effort\nto overthrow this uptight aud fear\nless judge who has already done so\nmuch for the good name of Amotion in\nChina. It is not too much to say tlint\nthis assault on Judge Wilfley in tho in\nterest of the vlnlous and criminal\nclasses is a public scandal.\"\nMany Suicides in Prussia.\nBerlin, .March Ik Statistics relative\nto suicides in Prussia during 1900 are\njust 'avutlablo and present some vary\nstriking figures. In twelve months no\nfewer t limit 7,298 persons, r,5S4 men\nand 1,714 women, ended thalr own\nlives.\nNine-Hour Law Must Hold.\nWashington, March 3. The inter\nstate commerce commission decided\nby a unanimous vote to deny all pe\ntitions for the extension of time with\nin which to comply with the so-called\nhours of service laws the nine-hour\nlaw.\nBought, and which has boon\nhas homo tho signature of\nhas heen mado under his pcrr\nSignature of\nCATARRH\nEly's Cream Balm\nSuro to Civo Satisfaction.\nGIVES RELIEF AT ONCE.\nIt oIimiiimw, Hooting, hi'nU and pnrtecfs tbo\ndieii-i'd ii,inlr!inon'iltiiiu front C'iturrb\nand ilrivi sawuy a Cold iu tin- Head quickly.\nIti'storo-J tho SoiiM--. of T.nto nnd SnielL\nKu-y to use Cuiit.uii't nn injurious drugs\nApplied into tho instills nnd absorbed.\nL.nu''' Size, FiO routs at Dnvuista or by\nin. '1 Liquid Cream Vilm for tif lit\nutomucrs, 75 cents.\nELY BROTHERS. 56 Warren St.. New York.\nL. SHERMAN,\nGeneral\nAuctioneer\nResidence: First door south of\nlied Cloud Mill, 101 South -Webster\nstreet.\nt'an bo found at home every fore\nnoon. Terms reasonable.\nDon't Buy Land nor loan\nMoney on Real Estate\nwithout getting' one of Teel's\nperfect Abstracts of Title. The\noldest and most reliable set of\nAbstract books in Webster Co.\nS10,(M;0 bond filed aud approved.\nRepresent. si. of the best In\nsurance companies doing busi\nness in the state.\nLOANS MAM 99 CITY PROPERTIES\nO- C. TEEL,\nRed Cloud, Nebr.\nOffice in Over Jug Block.\nPhones: Bell 98 f rarmcrs3G\nL\nUc4,\nTV IVvVtA9H\nS\n\nm","height":"28120","width":"18984"}}
